    "body": "Updates `example_init.lua`:\r\n\r\n- Consistently use `:h`\r\n- Align PLUGINS section with the overall style.\r\n  Since this entire file is example, all sections use declarative voice, avoiding \"For example\".\r\n  Replaces summary list with related help tags.\r\n- Adjust mini.completion URI\r\n  See https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.nvim/discussions/1970\r\n- Misc grammar fix",
    "closed_at": "2026-03-19T17:22:33Z",
    "comment_data": [],
    "comment_regular_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "@justinmk when I sent PR to add `example_init.lua`, I intentionally didn't recommend any 3rd-party plugins there, because it is intended to just instruct users on some basic features when configuring Nvim (options, creating command, mapping, autocmd, adding plugins). It is not meant to replace kickstart.nvim, which for sure has much larger scopes now.\r\n\r\nIf we follow kickstart.nvim way, we may have to deal with people who complain why Nvim recommends `fzf-lua` over `snacks.nvim`, etc https://github.com/nvim-lua/kickstart.nvim/pull/1481. And why does Nvim recommend `mini.completion`, while it already has 2 autocompletion engine (`vim.lsp.completion` and `'autocomplete'`)? If built-in features are so bad that Nvim recommends external plugins, shouldn't built-in features be improved instead?",
