        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> when I sent PR to add `example_init.lua`, I intentionally didn't recommend any 3rd-party plugins there, because it is intended to just instruct users on some basic features when configuring Nvim (options, creating command, mapping, autocmd, adding plugins). It is not meant to replace kickstart.nvim, which for sure has much larger scopes now.\r\n\r\n\"vim.pack\" was not a thing back then and was added to `example_init.lua` later in #34009. For most users, installing plugins is a required step, and builtin package manager solved the complications of setting up external ones like lazy.nvim.\r\n\r\n> If we follow kickstart.nvim way, we may have to deal with people who complain why Nvim recommends `fzf-lua` over `snacks.nvim`, etc [nvim-lua/kickstart.nvim#1481](https://github.com/nvim-lua/kickstart.nvim/pull/1481).\r\n\r\nBy looking at PR you provided \"kickstart.nvim way\" seems like becoming a distro. But here it's just example configuration file, and it's hardly recommendation to use what listed there and not something else. As long as the plugins are literally not abandoned and works I can't see any objections to edit them. But I agree that such list may add some maintainance cost without clear policy on what should be there, so maybe it is enough to put only 'neovim/nvim-lspconfig' as an example of `vim.pack.add` usage.\r\n\r\n> And why does Nvim recommend `mini.completion`, while it already has 2 autocompletion engine (`vim.lsp.completion` and `'autocomplete'`)? If built-in features are so bad that Nvim recommends external plugins, shouldn't built-in features be improved instead?\r\n\r\nBecause `mini.completion` offers features that are currently missing and that some users may find useful. Of course, built-ins should be improved, but there's usually a reason why certain functionality hasn't been included in the core yet. And again, I don't think the example config should be perceived as an official recommendation of the \"best\" or must-have plugins.",
